.SS " 1\&. Getting started"
.PP
.SS " 1\&.1\&. Using global headers"
.PP
GLM is a header-only library, and thus does not need to be compiled\&. We can use GLM's implementation of GLSL's mathematics functionality by including the \fC<\fBglm/glm\&.hpp\fP>\fP header:
.PP
.PP
.nf
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>
.fi
.PP
.PP
To extend the feature set supported by GLM and keeping the library as close to GLSL as possible, new features are implemented as extensions that can be included thought a separated header: 
.PP
.nf
// Include all GLM core / GLSL features
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp> // vec2, vec3, mat4, radians

// Include all GLM extensions
#include <glm/ext\&.hpp> // perspective, translate, rotate

glm::mat4 transform(glm::vec2 const& Orientation, glm::vec3 const& Translate, glm::vec3 const& Up)
{
    glm::mat4 Proj = glm::perspective(glm::radians(45\&.f), 1\&.33f, 0\&.1f, 10\&.f);
    glm::mat4 ViewTranslate = glm::translate(glm::mat4(1\&.f), Translate);
    glm::mat4 ViewRotateX = glm::rotate(ViewTranslate, Orientation\&.y, Up);
    glm::mat4 View = glm::rotate(ViewRotateX, Orientation\&.x, Up);
    glm::mat4 Model = glm::mat4(1\&.0f);
    return Proj * View * Model;
}

.fi
.PP
.PP
\fINote: Including \fC<\fBglm/glm\&.hpp\fP>\fP and \fC<\fBglm/ext\&.hpp\fP>\fP is convenient but pull a lot of code which will significantly increase build time, particularly if these files are included in all source files\&. We may prefer to use the approaches describe in the two following sections to keep the project build fast\&.\fP
.PP
.SS " 1\&.2\&. Using separated headers"
.PP
GLM relies on C++ templates heavily, and may significantly increase compilation times for projects that use it\&. Hence, user projects could only include the features they actually use\&. Following is the list of all the core features, based on GLSL specification, headers: 
.PP
.nf
#include <glm/vec2\&.hpp>               // vec2, bvec2, dvec2, ivec2 and uvec2
#include <glm/vec3\&.hpp>               // vec3, bvec3, dvec3, ivec3 and uvec3
#include <glm/vec4\&.hpp>               // vec4, bvec4, dvec4, ivec4 and uvec4
#include <glm/mat2x2\&.hpp>             // mat2, dmat2
#include <glm/mat2x3\&.hpp>             // mat2x3, dmat2x3
#include <glm/mat2x4\&.hpp>             // mat2x4, dmat2x4
#include <glm/mat3x2\&.hpp>             // mat3x2, dmat3x2
#include <glm/mat3x3\&.hpp>             // mat3, dmat3
#include <glm/mat3x4\&.hpp>             // mat3x4, dmat2
#include <glm/mat4x2\&.hpp>             // mat4x2, dmat4x2
#include <glm/mat4x3\&.hpp>             // mat4x3, dmat4x3
#include <glm/mat4x4\&.hpp>             // mat4, dmat4
#include <glm/common\&.hpp>             // all the GLSL common functions: abs, min, mix, isnan, fma, etc\&.
#include <glm/exponential\&.hpp>        // all the GLSL exponential functions: pow, log, exp2, sqrt, etc\&.
#include <glm/geometry\&.hpp>           // all the GLSL geometry functions: dot, cross, reflect, etc\&.
#include <glm/integer\&.hpp>            // all the GLSL integer functions: findMSB, bitfieldExtract, etc\&.
#include <glm/matrix\&.hpp>             // all the GLSL matrix functions: transpose, inverse, etc\&.
#include <glm/packing\&.hpp>            // all the GLSL packing functions: packUnorm4x8, unpackHalf2x16, etc\&.
#include <glm/trigonometric\&.hpp>      // all the GLSL trigonometric functions: radians, cos, asin, etc\&.
#include <glm/vector_relational\&.hpp>  // all the GLSL vector relational functions: equal, less, etc\&.

.fi
.PP
.PP
The following is a code sample using separated core headers and an extension: 
.PP
.nf
// Include GLM core features
#include <glm/vec2\&.hpp>           // vec2
#include <glm/vec3\&.hpp>           // vec3
#include <glm/mat4x4\&.hpp>         // mat4
#include <glm/trigonometric\&.hpp>  //radians

// Include GLM extension
#include <glm/ext/matrix_transform\&.hpp> // perspective, translate, rotate

glm::mat4 transform(glm::vec2 const& Orientation, glm::vec3 const& Translate, glm::vec3 const& Up)
{
    glm::mat4 Proj = glm::perspective(glm::radians(45\&.f), 1\&.33f, 0\&.1f, 10\&.f);
    glm::mat4 ViewTranslate = glm::translate(glm::mat4(1\&.f), Translate);
    glm::mat4 ViewRotateX = glm::rotate(ViewTranslate, Orientation\&.y, Up);
    glm::mat4 View = glm::rotate(ViewRotateX, Orientation\&.x, Up);
    glm::mat4 Model = glm::mat4(1\&.0f);
    return Proj * View * Model;
}

.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 1\&.3\&. Using extension headers"
.PP
Using GLM through split headers to minimize the project build time: 
.PP
.nf
// Include GLM vector extensions:
#include <glm/ext/vector_float2\&.hpp>                // vec2
#include <glm/ext/vector_float3\&.hpp>                // vec3
#include <glm/ext/vector_trigonometric\&.hpp>         // radians

// Include GLM matrix extensions:
#include <glm/ext/matrix_float4x4\&.hpp>              // mat4
#include <glm/ext/matrix_transform\&.hpp>             // perspective, translate, rotate

glm::mat4 transform(glm::vec2 const& Orientation, glm::vec3 const& Translate, glm::vec3 const& Up)
{
    glm::mat4 Proj = glm::perspective(glm::radians(45\&.f), 1\&.33f, 0\&.1f, 10\&.f);
    glm::mat4 ViewTranslate = glm::translate(glm::mat4(1\&.f), Translate);
    glm::mat4 ViewRotateX = glm::rotate(ViewTranslate, Orientation\&.y, Up);
    glm::mat4 View = glm::rotate(ViewRotateX, Orientation\&.x, Up);
    glm::mat4 Model = glm::mat4(1\&.0f);
    return Proj * View * Model;
}

.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 1\&.4\&. Dependencies"
.PP
GLM does not depend on external libraries or headers such as \fC<GL/gl\&.h>\fP, \fC\fC<GL/glcorearb\&.h>\fP\fP, \fC<GLES3/gl3\&.h>\fP, \fC<GL/glu\&.h>\fP, or \fC<windows\&.h>\fP\&.
.PP
.PP
  
.PP
.SS " 2\&. Preprocessor configurations"
.PP
.SS " 2\&.1\&. GLM_FORCE_MESSAGES: Platform auto detection and default configuration"
.PP
When included, GLM will first automatically detect the compiler used, the C++ standard supported, the compiler arguments used to configure itself matching the build environment\&.
.PP
For example, if the compiler arguments request AVX code generation, GLM will rely on its code path providing AVX optimizations when available\&.
.PP
We can change GLM configuration using specific C++ preprocessor defines that must be declared before including any GLM headers\&.
.PP
Using \fCGLM_FORCE_MESSAGES\fP, GLM will report the configuration as part of the build log\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_MESSAGES // Or defined when building (e\&.g\&. -DGLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE)
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>
.fi
.PP
.PP
Example of configuration log generated by \fCGLM_FORCE_MESSAGES\fP: 
.PP
.nf
GLM: version 0\&.9\&.9\&.1
GLM: C++ 17 with extensions
GLM: Clang compiler detected
GLM: x86 64 bits with AVX instruction set build target
GLM: Linux platform detected
GLM: GLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE is undefined\&. swizzling functions or operators are disabled\&.
GLM: GLM_FORCE_SIZE_T_LENGTH is undefined\&. \&.length() returns a glm::length_t, a typedef of int following GLSL\&.
GLM: GLM_FORCE_UNRESTRICTED_GENTYPE is undefined\&. Follows strictly GLSL on valid function genTypes\&.
GLM: GLM_FORCE_DEPTH_ZERO_TO_ONE is undefined\&. Using negative one to one depth clip space\&.
GLM: GLM_FORCE_LEFT_HANDED is undefined\&. Using right handed coordinate system\&.

.fi
.PP
.PP
The following subsections describe each configurations and defines\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.2\&. GLM_FORCE_PLATFORM_UNKNOWN: Force GLM to no detect the build platform"
.PP
\fCGLM_FORCE_PLATFORM_UNKNOWN\fP prevents GLM from detecting the build platform\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.3\&. GLM_FORCE_COMPILER_UNKNOWN: Force GLM to no detect the C++ compiler"
.PP
\fCGLM_FORCE_COMPILER_UNKNOWN\fP prevents GLM from detecting the C++ compiler\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.4\&. GLM_FORCE_ARCH_UNKNOWN: Force GLM to no detect the build architecture"
.PP
\fCGLM_FORCE_ARCH_UNKNOWN\fP prevents GLM from detecting the build target architecture\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.5\&. GLM_FORCE_CXX_UNKNOWN: Force GLM to no detect the C++ standard"
.PP
\fCGLM_FORCE_CSS_UNKNOWN\fP prevents GLM from detecting the C++ compiler standard support\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.6\&. GLM_FORCE_CXX**: C++ language detection"
.PP
GLM will automatically take advantage of compilers’ language extensions when enabled\&. To increase cross platform compatibility and to avoid compiler extensions, a programmer can define \fCGLM_FORCE_CXX98\fP before any inclusion of \fC<\fBglm/glm\&.hpp\fP>\fP to restrict the language feature set C++98:
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_CXX98
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>
.fi
.PP
.PP
For C++11, C++14, and C++17 equivalent defines are available:
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCGLM_FORCE_CXX11\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCGLM_FORCE_CXX14\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCGLM_FORCE_CXX17\fP
.PP
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_CXX11
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

// If the compiler doesn’t support C++11, compiler errors will happen\&.
.fi
.PP
.PP
\fCGLM_FORCE_CXX17\fP overrides \fCGLM_FORCE_CXX14\fP; \fCGLM_FORCE_CXX14\fP overrides \fCGLM_FORCE_CXX11\fP; and \fCGLM_FORCE_CXX11\fP overrides \fCGLM_FORCE_CXX98\fP defines\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.7\&. GLM_FORCE_EXPLICIT_CTOR: Requiring explicit conversions"
.PP
GLSL supports implicit conversions of vector and matrix types\&. For example, an ivec4 can be implicitly converted into \fCvec4\fP\&.
.PP
Often, this behaviour is not desirable but following the spirit of the library, this is the default behavior in GLM\&. However, GLM 0\&.9\&.6 introduced the define \fCGLM_FORCE_EXPLICIT_CTOR\fP to require explicit conversion for GLM types\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

void foo()
{
    glm::ivec4 a;
    \&.\&.\&.

    glm::vec4 b(a); // Explicit conversion, OK
    glm::vec4 c = a; // Implicit conversion, OK
    \&.\&.\&.
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
With \fCGLM_FORCE_EXPLICIT_CTOR\fP define, implicit conversions are not allowed:
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_EXPLICIT_CTOR
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

void foo()
{
    glm::ivec4 a;
    {
        glm::vec4 b(a); // Explicit conversion, OK
        glm::vec4 c = a; // Implicit conversion, ERROR
        \&.\&.\&.
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.8\&. GLM_FORCE_INLINE: Force inline"
.PP
To push further the software performance, a programmer can define \fCGLM_FORCE_INLINE\fP before any inclusion of \fC<\fBglm/glm\&.hpp\fP>\fP to force the compiler to inline GLM code\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_INLINE
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>
.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.9\&. GLM_FORCE_ALIGNED_GENTYPES: Force GLM to enable aligned types"
.PP
Every object type has the property called alignment requirement, which is an integer value (of type \fCstd::size_t\fP, always a power of 2) representing the number of bytes between successive addresses at which objects of this type can be allocated\&. The alignment requirement of a type can be queried with alignof or \fCstd::alignment_of\fP\&. The pointer alignment function \fCstd::align\fP can be used to obtain a suitably-aligned pointer within some buffer, and \fCstd::aligned_storage\fP can be used to obtain suitably-aligned storage\&.
.PP
Each object type imposes its alignment requirement on every object of that type; stricter alignment (with larger alignment requirement) can be requested using C++11 \fCalignas\fP\&.
.PP
In order to satisfy alignment requirements of all non-static members of a class, padding may be inserted after some of its members\&.
.PP
GLM supports both packed and aligned types\&. Packed types allow filling data structure without inserting extra padding\&. Aligned GLM types align addresses based on the size of the value type of a GLM type\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_ALIGNED_GENTYPES
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>
#include <glm/gtc/type_aligned\&.hpp>

typedef glm::aligned_vec4 vec4a;
typedef glm::packed_vec4 vec4p;
.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.10\&. GLM_FORCE_DEFAULT_ALIGNED_GENTYPES: Force GLM to use aligned types by default"
.PP
GLM allows using aligned types by default for vector types using \fCGLM_FORCE_DEFAULT_ALIGNED_GENTYPES\fP:
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_DEFAULT_ALIGNED_GENTYPES
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

struct MyStruct
{
    glm::vec4 a;
    float b;
    glm::vec3 c;
};

void foo()
{
    printf("MyStruct requires memory padding: %d bytes\n", sizeof(MyStruct));
}

>>> MyStruct requires memory padding: 48 bytes
.fi
.PP
.PP
.PP
.nf
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

struct MyStruct
{
    glm::vec4 a;
    float b;
    glm::vec3 c;
