void foo()
{
    printf("MyStruct is tightly packed: %d bytes\n", sizeof(MyStruct));
}

>>> MyStruct is tightly packed: 32 bytes
.fi
.PP
.PP
\fINote: GLM SIMD optimizations require the use of aligned types\fP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.11\&. GLM_FORCE_INTRINSICS: Using SIMD optimizations"
.PP
GLM provides some SIMD optimizations based on \fCcompiler intrinsics\fP\&. These optimizations will be automatically thanks to compiler arguments when \fCGLM_FORCE_INTRINSICS\fP is defined before including GLM files\&. For example, if a program is compiled with Visual Studio using \fC/arch:AVX\fP, GLM will detect this argument and generate code using AVX instructions automatically when available\&.
.PP
It’s possible to avoid the instruction set detection by forcing the use of a specific instruction set with one of the fallowing define: \fCGLM_FORCE_SSE2\fP, \fCGLM_FORCE_SSE3\fP, \fCGLM_FORCE_SSSE3\fP, \fCGLM_FORCE_SSE41\fP, \fCGLM_FORCE_SSE42\fP, \fCGLM_FORCE_AVX\fP, \fCGLM_FORCE_AVX2\fP or \fCGLM_FORCE_AVX512\fP\&.
.PP
The use of intrinsic functions by GLM implementation can be avoided using the define \fCGLM_FORCE_PURE\fP before any inclusion of GLM headers\&. This can be particularly useful if we want to rely on C++14 \fCconstexpr\fP\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_PURE
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

static_assert(glm::vec4::length() == 4, "Using GLM C++ 14 constexpr support for compile time tests");

// GLM code will be compiled using pure C++ code without any intrinsics
.fi
.PP
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_SIMD_AVX2
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

// If the compiler doesn’t support AVX2 instrinsics, compiler errors will happen\&.
.fi
.PP
.PP
Additionally, GLM provides a low level SIMD API in glm/simd directory for users who are really interested in writing fast algorithms\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.12\&. GLM_FORCE_PRECISION_**: Default precision"
.PP
C++ does not provide a way to implement GLSL default precision selection (as defined in GLSL 4\&.10 specification section 4\&.5\&.3) with GLSL-like syntax\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
precision mediump int;
precision highp float;
.fi
.PP
.PP
To use the default precision functionality, GLM provides some defines that need to added before any include of \fC\fBglm\&.hpp\fP\fP:
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_PRECISION_MEDIUMP_INT
#define GLM_FORCE_PRECISION_HIGHP_FLOAT
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>
.fi
.PP
.PP
Available defines for floating point types (\fC\fBglm::vec\fP\\*\fP, \fC\fBglm::mat\fP\\*\fP):
.PP
