\fCGLM_FORCE_PRECISION_HIGHP_UINT\fP: High precision (default)
.PP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.13\&. GLM_FORCE_SINGLE_ONLY: Removed explicit 64-bits floating point types"
.PP
Some platforms (Dreamcast) doesn't support double precision floating point values\&. To compile on such platforms, GCC has the \fC--m4-single-only\fP build argument\&. When defining \fCGLM_FORCE_SINGLE_ONLY\fP before including GLM headers, GLM releases the requirement of double precision floating point values support\&. Effectivement, all the float64 types are no longer defined and double behaves like float\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.14\&. GLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE: Enable swizzle operators"
.PP
Shader languages like GLSL often feature so-called swizzle expressions, which may be used to freely select and arrange a vector's components\&. For example, \fCvariable\&.x\fP, \fCvariable\&.xzy\fP and \fCvariable\&.zxyy\fP respectively form a scalar, a 3D vector and a 4D vector\&. The result of a swizzle expression in GLSL can be either an R-value or an L-value\&. Swizzle expressions can be written with characters from exactly one of \fCxyzw\fP (usually for positions), \fCrgba\fP (usually for colors), and \fCstpq\fP (usually for texture coordinates)\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
vec4 A;
vec2 B;

B\&.yx = A\&.wy;
B = A\&.xx;
vec3 C = A\&.bgr;
vec3 D = B\&.rsz; // Invalid, won't compile
.fi
.PP
.PP
GLM supports some of this functionality\&. Swizzling can be enabled by defining \fCGLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE\fP\&.
.PP
\fINote: Enabling swizzle expressions will massively increase the size of your binaries and the time it takes to compile them!\fP
.PP
GLM has two levels of swizzling support described in the following subsections\&.
.PP
.SS "2\&.14\&.1\&. Swizzle functions for standard C++ 98"
.PP
When compiling GLM as C++98, R-value swizzle expressions are simulated through member functions of each vector type\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE // Or defined when building (e\&.g\&. -DGLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE)
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

void foo()
{
    glm::vec4 const ColorRGBA = glm::vec4(1\&.0f, 0\&.5f, 0\&.0f, 1\&.0f);
    glm::vec3 const ColorBGR = ColorRGBA\&.bgr();

    glm::vec3 const PositionA = glm::vec3(1\&.0f, 0\&.5f, 0\&.0f);
    glm::vec3 const PositionB = PositionXYZ\&.xyz() * 2\&.0f;

    glm::vec2 const TexcoordST = glm::vec2(1\&.0f, 0\&.5f);
    glm::vec4 const TexcoordSTPQ = TexcoordST\&.stst();
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
Swizzle operators return a \fBcopy\fP of the component values, and thus \fIcan't\fP be used as L-values to change a vector's values\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

void foo()
{
  glm::vec3 const A = glm::vec3(1\&.0f, 0\&.5f, 0\&.0f);

  // No compiler error, but A is not modified\&.
  // An anonymous copy is being modified (and then discarded)\&.
  A\&.bgr() = glm::vec3(2\&.0f, 1\&.5f, 1\&.0f); // A is not modified!
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS "2\&.14\&.2\&. Swizzle operations for C++ 98 with language extensions"
.PP
Visual C++, GCC and Clang support, as a \fInon-standard language extension\fP, anonymous \fCstruct\fPs as \fCunion\fP members\&. This permits a powerful swizzling implementation that both allows L-value swizzle expressions and GLSL-like syntax\&. To use this feature, the language extension must be enabled by a supporting compiler and \fCGLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE\fP must be \fC#define\fPd\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

// Only guaranteed to work with Visual C++!
// Some compilers that support Microsoft extensions may compile this\&.
void foo()
{
  glm::vec4 ColorRGBA = glm::vec4(1\&.0f, 0\&.5f, 0\&.0f, 1\&.0f);

  // l-value:
  glm::vec4 ColorBGRA = ColorRGBA\&.bgra;

  // r-value:
  ColorRGBA\&.bgra = ColorRGBA;

  // Both l-value and r-value
  ColorRGBA\&.bgra = ColorRGBA\&.rgba;
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
This version returns implementation-specific objects that \fIimplicitly convert\fP to their respective vector types\&. As a consequence of this design, these extra types \fBcan't be directly used\fP as C++ function arguments; they must be converted through constructors or \fCoperator()\fP\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_SWIZZLE
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

using namespace glm;

void foo()
{
  vec4 Color = vec4(1\&.0f, 0\&.5f, 0\&.0f, 1\&.0f);

  // Generates compiler errors\&. Color\&.rgba is not a vector type\&.
  vec4 ClampedA = clamp(Color\&.rgba, 0\&.f, 1\&.f); // ERROR

  // Explicit conversion through a constructor
  vec4 ClampedB = clamp(vec4(Color\&.rgba), 0\&.f, 1\&.f); // OK

  // Explicit conversion through operator()
  vec4 ClampedC = clamp(Color\&.rgba(), 0\&.f, 1\&.f); // OK
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
\fINote: The implementation has a caveat: Swizzle operator types must be different on both size of the equal operator or the operation will fail\&. There is no known fix for this issue to date\fP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.15\&. GLM_FORCE_XYZW_ONLY: Only exposes x, y, z and w components"
.PP
Following GLSL specifications, GLM supports three sets of components to access vector types member: x, y, z, w; r, g, b, a; and s, t, p, q\&. Also, this is making vector component very expressive in the code, it may make debugging vector types a little cubersom as the debuggers will typically display three time the values for each compoenents due to the existence of the three sets\&.
.PP
To simplify vector types, GLM allows exposing only x, y, z and w components thanks to \fCGLM_FORCE_XYZW_ONLY\fP define\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.16\&. GLM_FORCE_LEFT_HANDED: Force left handed coordinate system"
.PP
By default, OpenGL is using a right handed coordinate system\&. However, others APIs such as Direct3D have done different choice and relies on the left handed coordinate system\&.
.PP
GLM allows switching the coordinate system to left handed by defining \fCGLM_FORCE_LEFT_HANDED\fP\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.17\&. GLM_FORCE_DEPTH_ZERO_TO_ONE: Force the use of a clip space between 0 to 1"
.PP
By default, OpenGL is using a -1 to 1 clip space in Z-axis\&. However, others APIs such as Direct3D relies on a clip space between 0 to 1 in Z-axis\&.
.PP
GLM allows switching the clip space in Z-axis to 0 to 1 by defining \fCGLM_FORCE_DEPTH_ZERO_TO_ONE\fP\&.
.PP
.SS " 2\&.18\&. GLM_FORCE_SIZE_T_LENGTH: Vector and matrix static size"
.PP
GLSL supports the member function \&.\fBlength()\fP for all vector and matrix types\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

void foo(vec4 const& v)
{
    int Length = v\&.length();
    \&.\&.\&.
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
This function returns an \fCint\fP however this function typically interacts with STL \fCsize_t\fP based code\&. GLM provides \fCGLM_FORCE_SIZE_T_LENGTH\fP pre-processor configuration so that member functions \fC\fBlength()\fP\fP return a \fCsize_t\fP\&.
.PP
Additionally, GLM defines the type \fCglm::length_t\fP to identify \fC\fBlength()\fP\fP returned type, independently from \fCGLM_FORCE_SIZE_T_LENGTH\fP\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_SIZE_T_LENGTH
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

void foo(vec4 const& v)
{
    glm::length_t Length = v\&.length();
    \&.\&.\&.
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.19\&. GLM_FORCE_UNRESTRICTED_GENTYPE: Removing genType restriction"
.PP
GLSL has restrictions on types supported by certain functions that may appear excessive\&. By default, GLM follows the GLSL specification as accurately as possible however it's possible to relax these rules using \fCGLM_FORCE_UNRESTRICTED_GENTYPE\fP define\&.
.PP
.PP
.nf
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

float average(float const A, float const B)
{
    return glm::mix(A, B, 0\&.5f); // By default glm::mix only supports floating-point types
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
By defining GLM_FORCE_UNRESTRICTED_GENTYPE, we allow using integer types:
.PP
.PP
.nf
#define GLM_FORCE_UNRESTRICTED_GENTYPE
#include <glm/glm\&.hpp>

int average(int const A, int const B)
{
    return glm::mix(A, B, 0\&.5f); // integers are ok thanks to GLM_FORCE_UNRESTRICTED_GENTYPE
}
.fi
.PP
.PP
.SS " 2\&.20\&. GLM_FORCE_SILENT_WARNINGS: Silent C++ warnings from language extensions"
.PP
When using /W4 on Visual C++ or -Wpedantic on GCC, for example, the compilers will generate warnings for using C++ language extensions (/Za with Visual C++) such as anonymous struct\&. GLM relies on anonymous structs for swizzle operators and aligned vector types\&. To silent those warnings define \fCGLM_FORCE_SILENT_WARNINGS\fP before including GLM headers\&.
.PP
.PP
  
